<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-877-794  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 877 794.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  Nov 20 1989 n3134 p139(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The East bloc's $100 billion phone bill. (Western companiesattempt deals to upgrade obsolete communications systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schares, Gail E.; Brady, Rose; Maremont, Mark; Peterson, Thane;Keller, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The East bloc's considerable lack of telephones is promptingWestern companies to attempt deals to upgrade Soviettelecommunications.andP;  Given his urgent need to provide moreconsumer goods, Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev most likelycannot afford the requisite $96 billion to put a phone in everySoviet home by the year 2000.andP;  The Soviet idea of linking Japanand Europe with a 11,000-mile, high-speed, trans-Siberianfiber-optic cable would update the Soviet system quickly whilebringing in hard-currency revenues.andP;  The largest immediateobstacle to phone modernization is whether suppliers can winapprovals from the Paris-based Coordinating Committee onMultilateral Export Controls (Cocom).andP;  US policymakers continue toresist pressure from Europe and Japan to relax Cocom regulations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information ProcessingTelephone systemsSoviet UnionUpgradingCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsInternationalUnited StatesContractsTelecommunicationsGovernment Regulation.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   Number of East bloc phone lines and planned telecommunicationsspending. (chart)Person:    Gorbachev, Mikhail (decision making).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>